#week-title("Three", "Contributing to the Living Tradition")

=== Core Teaching

Every practitioner who maintains honest records, documents their preparations
faithfully, and shares their genuine observations with other practitioners is
contributing to the living tradition — regardless of whether those observations
are dramatic or modest.

The alchemical tradition has been sustained across centuries not through a
chain of spectacular discoveries, but through the patient accumulation of
careful observation by practitioners who recorded what they actually saw and
shared it honestly. The PRS Bulletins — issued monthly by Frater Albertus
across twelve years — are not a collection of breakthroughs. They are a
collection of honest, specific, practical observations shared consistently
over time. Their value derives entirely from their honesty and their
consistency.

*What constitutes a genuine contribution.* The practitioner who has completed
three years of careful work and maintained a full laboratory journal has, in
those journals, something genuinely worth contributing to the tradition:

- *Observations not previously recorded:* The specific behaviour of particular
  preparations under specific conditions — the exact colour of a copper acetate
  cohobation after four weeks under a water bath; the way a particular batch of
  Melissa calcined differently from another because of ambient humidity. These
  observations are specific and may be useful to another practitioner working
  with the same materials.
- *Errors and their consequences:* The tradition learns from failure as much as
  from success. A carefully documented preparation failure — with a precise
  account of what went wrong and why — is a contribution. The student who
  vitrified their first calcination and documented it precisely has given future
  practitioners something the texts alone cannot provide.
- *The inner-outer correlations:* If the practitioner has observed genuine
  correlations between their inner state and their preparation's behaviour, and
  has documented these consistently enough to have confidence in them, these
  observations belong to the tradition's growing understanding of the
  practitioner's role in the Work.

*How to share.* Through the academy's community (the shared journal, quarterly
gatherings, correspondence with other practitioners). Through eventual formal
publication, if the practitioner reaches a stage where they have enough material
to warrant it. Through guiding other practitioners, sharing specific observations
that are relevant to where the guided practitioner currently stands.

=== Topics This Week

- Patient accumulation of honest observation as the tradition's sustaining mechanism
- What constitutes a genuine contribution: observations, errors, correlations
- How to share: community channels, eventual publication, guiding others
- The Materia Medica notebook as a contribution in itself

#inner-work[
  *Identifying Your Contribution*

  Review your laboratory journal and Materia Medica notebook. Identify three
  specific observations — from any point across the three years — that you
  believe are genuinely worth sharing with another practitioner. They need not
  be dramatic. They need only be honest, specific, and unlikely to be available
  in the existing texts.

  Record these three observations clearly in your journal, formatted as if
  you were sharing them with a colleague: what was the preparation, what were
  the conditions, and what did you observe?
]

